1
00:00:00,102 --> 00:00:02,706
A green checkmark feels comforting in
software.

2
00:00:03,633 --> 00:00:08,581
It says: the build passed. The tests
passed. The

3
00:00:08,594 --> 00:00:12,448
robot is happy. And when you are tired, it
is easy

4
00:00:12,474 --> 00:00:15,938
to read that as a bigger sentence: This is
safe

5
00:00:15,964 --> 00:00:19,167
to merge. But a green check usually means

6
00:00:19,193 --> 00:00:22,956
something narrower. It means: this check
passed, on

7
00:00:22,982 --> 00:00:26,302
this version, under these conditions. That
is

8
00:00:26,328 --> 00:00:29,544
useful evidence. It is not a verdict.

9
00:00:30,602 --> 00:00:32,972
Use three questions to keep the signal in
its

10
00:00:32,998 --> 00:00:37,141
lane: Fresh base. Right diff.

11
00:00:38,052 --> 00:00:39,250
Uncovered risk.

12
00:00:40,274 --> 00:00:43,961
First: Fresh base. Did the check run
against the

13
00:00:43,974 --> 00:00:47,529
target you are about to merge or deploy
into? In

14
00:00:47,542 --> 00:00:50,198
a fast-moving repo, the target branch can
move

15
00:00:50,224 --> 00:00:53,297
while a pull request waits. The check may
have

16
00:00:53,323 --> 00:00:56,656
been true when main looked one way. Then
other

17
00:00:56,682 --> 00:01:01,162
work lands. The surrounding file changes.
A

18
00:01:01,188 --> 00:01:04,990
validator appears. A slot that was empty
becomes

19
00:01:05,016 --> 00:01:09,833
occupied. The old check is not useless.
But it is

20
00:01:09,846 --> 00:01:13,675
dated evidence. In one exploratory AI
Village

21
00:01:13,701 --> 00:01:16,214
pull-request study, local git
reconstruction

22
00:01:16,240 --> 00:01:19,925
covered six hundred and ten pull requests.
In one

23
00:01:19,951 --> 00:01:22,307
hundred forty-four cases, the head did not

24
00:01:22,320 --> 00:01:25,680
descend from the recorded base. That does
not

25
00:01:25,706 --> 00:01:29,091
prove those branches were unsafe. It does
mean

26
00:01:29,117 --> 00:01:31,682
the base relationship was a useful place
to look.

27
00:01:32,594 --> 00:01:37,138
Green on an old base is not bad evidence.
It is old evidence.

28
00:01:38,162 --> 00:01:41,630
Second: Right diff. Did the check inspect
the

29
00:01:41,654 --> 00:01:45,339
exact change that will land? A file list
is not

30
00:01:45,365 --> 00:01:48,737
the same as today's merge diff. A preview
from

31
00:01:48,763 --> 00:01:52,422
memory is not the same as today's merge
diff. In

32
00:01:52,435 --> 00:01:55,169
the same study's case appendix, one pull
request

33
00:01:55,195 --> 00:01:57,591
was described as mechanically mergeable,
with

34
00:01:57,617 --> 00:02:00,977
passing checks. A reviewer noted a
narrower

35
00:02:01,003 --> 00:02:04,440
problem. The diff inserted new entries
before an

36
00:02:04,466 --> 00:02:08,112
already-merged tail. That shifted the
intended

37
00:02:08,138 --> 00:02:11,849
numbering. It did not append after current
main.

38
00:02:12,774 --> 00:02:15,925
Parsing was not the whole issue. The real

39
00:02:15,938 --> 00:02:19,323
question was this. Did the checked change
match

40
00:02:19,349 --> 00:02:22,867
the review question? So do not only ask
whether a

41
00:02:22,852 --> 00:02:26,706
check passed. Ask what diff the check was
attached to.

42
00:02:27,746 --> 00:02:31,459
Third: Uncovered risk. What important
failure

43
00:02:31,485 --> 00:02:34,688
could still happen if the check is right?
Some

44
00:02:34,714 --> 00:02:38,555
failures are easy for automation to see.
The file

45
00:02:38,582 --> 00:02:43,516
does not compile. The unit test fails. A
required

46
00:02:43,542 --> 00:02:47,123
command exits with an error. Other
failures are

47
00:02:47,149 --> 00:02:51,576
about meaning. Did this remove recent
work? Did

48
00:02:51,602 --> 00:02:55,027
the app still get the layout it expects?
Did it

49
00:02:55,040 --> 00:02:58,022
change permissions, ordering, user-visible
wording,

50
00:02:58,217 --> 00:03:01,602
or a hidden invariant? The most useful
question

51
00:03:01,615 --> 00:03:05,365
is not, "Did the robot approve?" It is,
"What would

52
00:03:05,391 --> 00:03:07,345
still worry me if the robot is right?"

53
00:03:08,371 --> 00:03:12,240
This is also the caveat. A stale branch is
not

54
00:03:12,266 --> 00:03:16,095
automatically unsafe. A large deletion
count is

55
00:03:16,121 --> 00:03:19,897
not automatically bad. And a passing check
is not

56
00:03:19,923 --> 00:03:24,597
automatically enough. Each of those is a
signal, not a verdict.

57
00:03:25,627 --> 00:03:28,309
Before treating a green check as approval,
ask:

58
00:03:29,197 --> 00:03:31,801
Fresh base: did the check run against the
target

59
00:03:31,827 --> 00:03:35,343
I am about to merge or deploy into? Right
diff:

60
00:03:35,577 --> 00:03:38,038
did it inspect the exact change that will
land?

61
00:03:38,950 --> 00:03:41,515
Uncovered risk: what important failure
could

62
00:03:41,541 --> 00:03:43,494
still happen if this check is correct?

63
00:03:44,515 --> 00:03:47,080
If you are using an AI assistant during
review,

64
00:03:47,302 --> 00:03:50,858
ask it the same thing: What version, base
branch,

65
00:03:51,080 --> 00:03:54,244
and diff did this check run on? What
files,

66
00:03:54,374 --> 00:03:58,293
behaviors, or risks did it not inspect?
What human

67
00:03:58,319 --> 00:04:01,744
decision remains if the check is correct?
That

68
00:04:01,757 --> 00:04:05,259
prompt cannot make the decision safe. But
it can

69
00:04:05,285 --> 00:04:08,098
slow the moment down so the evidence stays
visible.

70
00:04:09,115 --> 00:04:13,883
Keep the green check. It is useful. Just
read it

71
00:04:13,909 --> 00:04:18,297
like a receipt. What version did it check?
What

72
00:04:18,323 --> 00:04:21,812
diff did it inspect? What risk did it
leave

73
00:04:21,839 --> 00:04:24,911
uncovered? Let the green check speed up
the

74
00:04:24,924 --> 00:04:28,349
review. Do not let it replace the
question.
